<ques id="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2001-10-04.5691.q0" oldstyleid="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2001-10-04.798W.4" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/1036" speakername="David Laws" colnum="798W"  url="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011004/text/11004w01.htm#11004w01.html_wqn8">
	<p pid=".798W.4/1" qnum="5691">To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department what targets he has set for the total size of the police force in England for each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.</p>
</ques>

<gidredirect oldgid="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2001-10-04.798W.5" newgid="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2001-10-04.5691.r0" matchtype="oldwransgid"/>
<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2001-10-04.5691.r0" oldstyleid="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2001-10-04.798W.5" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/851" speakername="John Denham" colnum="798W"  url="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011004/text/11004w01.htm#11004w01.html_spnew8">
	<p pid=".798W.5/1" class="holdinganswer">holding answer <phrase class="date" code="2001-07-20">20 July 2001</phrase></p>
	<p pid=".798W.5/2">On the basis of force projections, we expect police strength to reach record numbers by March 2003 (more than 128,300) and at least 130,000 officers by March 2004.</p>
</reply>
